questions.scenario:
A docs SPA works at `/`, but a pasted deep link returns 404:

```nginx
server {
    root /var/www/docs;
    index index.html;

    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
    }
}
```

The file `/var/www/docs/index.html` exists. Which `try_files` line fixes client-side routes while preserving real file checks?

A teammate proposes this shortcut for a SPA:

```nginx
location / {
    try_files /index.html;
}
```

What problem does this introduce compared with the article's pattern?

A static-site review contains this Nginx block:

```nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name docs.example.com;
    root /var/www/docs;
    index index.html;

    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;
    }
}
```

Which comments are accurate?

A combined Nginx config has an API proxy and a SPA fallback:

```nginx
location /api/ {
    proxy_pass http://localhost:3000;
}

location / {
    root /var/www/example/dist;
    try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;
}
```

Why is this structure better than placing the SPA fallback in the `/api/` location?
